We really try to limit using root as much as possible because fat fingers cause fat problems - especially on production systems, which is why we like the new installer creating the jira user, directory and service. We also appreciate the higher security of keeping critical configuration files under a separate entity from the application's userid.
Unfortunately when running the installer as root the installation directory is owned by root (except for a few directories owned by jira). This means that the JIRA administrator would be required to have root access to preform tasks such as installing a JIRA System I plugin.

I would suggest providing the ability to create a second jira account such as jiraadmin that would own the contents of the installation directory (which are not owned by jira) rather than using root.

